[{"sha":"96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"CI: Add broken link checking job for website content

This adds a CI job for running the new PR link checker for documentation.

[terraform-website PR 1574](https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform-website/pull/1574)
added a new link checking CI job specifically for warning about broken links in
pull requests. This link checker is optimized for:

- Running (relatively) quickly.
- Only reporting on files that were changed in the current PR, to avoid spamming
  you with problems you had nothing to do with.
- Being transparent and simple to maintain. (Note that this is in conflict with
  minimizing false positives/negatives! We try to give very few of both, but
  completely eliminating them would result in an unaffordable maintenance
  burden. We expect that some PRs will be merged with this job red.)

The tool is somewhat specific to our Middleman site builder, and we expect it
will be replaced or obviated in the transition to the Next.js platform... but in
the meantime, it should help make documentation slightly easier to maintain.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dweomer/terraform/commits/96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6"},{"sha":"bf5522aaec0b90de0264f2081fa1814332707d5e","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove website-test task from Makefile

[{"sha":"96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"CI: Add broken link checking job for website content

This adds a CI job for running the new PR link checker for documentation.

[terraform-website PR 1574](https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform-website/pull/1574)
added a new link checking CI job specifically for warning about broken links in
pull requests. This link checker is optimized for:

- Running (relatively) quickly.
- Only reporting on files that were changed in the current PR, to avoid spamming
  you with problems you had nothing to do with.
- Being transparent and simple to maintain. (Note that this is in conflict with
  minimizing false positives/negatives! We try to give very few of both, but
  completely eliminating them would result in an unaffordable maintenance
  burden. We expect that some PRs will be merged with this job red.)

The tool is somewhat specific to our Middleman site builder, and we expect it
will be replaced or obviated in the transition to the Next.js platform... but in
the meantime, it should help make documentation slightly easier to maintain.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6"},{"sha":"bf5522aaec0b90de0264f2081fa1814332707d5e","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove website-test task from Makefile

[{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: Id906c5a19e299a6236c28e8bc368b19d5e34a56e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sujitahirrao/tensorflow/commits/a4c1164634eb754b5192586b9c24c4e95cda8b7c"},{"sha":"b38e885409c02ee6a43604c3a9f37fc98e925315","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Preserve TPUDistributedVariables passed to TPUStrategy.run().

Normally run() converts all inputs to Tensor, which uses the current value of a variable.
Disabling the cast doesn't work, as a lower MLIR op will cast the variable to Tensor anyway.
Instead we partially apply any TPUDistributedVariables to the function before replicating the remaining inputs.

This doesn't enable any new functionality per se, as it was always possible to implicitly capture the variables in the Python function, but this matches behavior to MirroredStrategy and avoids a simple usability issue.

Note that this change of behavior might break anyone who was relying on the automatic cast happening, in which case the user-side fix would be to manually cast.

The Filesystems API compatibility module provides implementations for
Filesystem#getActions for several filesystems. Most filesystem
implementations are covered by the implementation in
AbstractFileSystemCompat, but this does not cover implementations
directly inheriting from Filesystem.

One such filesystem is BinaryFS.

In the SQL Editor the command window function (temp files for SQL
execution) is backed by a file in the SystemFileSystem, which delegates
in the end to BinaryFS:

SystemFileSystem->
  ModuleLayeredFileSystem ->
    BinaryFS

As BinaryFS does not implement getActions and no patch is provided for
this class, an AbstractMethodError is raised.

Instead of bailing out with an Error, the compatibility implementation
now returns an empty array to satisfy the Filesystem#getActions contract.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lkishalmi/netbeans/commits/2601979e6a3e404aec448b5406442bd3c85f6d9d"},{"sha":"90d1c35f1b3eb32bfcba92f0b8dad1005abd3f47","author":{"name":"Junichi Yamamoto","email":"b167b8eb530b93e72c6c0e9a10d8503b2e9a4f7e@apache.org"},"message":"[NETBEANS-4444] The selected text is not removed in the Find Combobox when text is input via IME

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"},{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source

instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

both channels.

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases
are downloaded from npm, nt CI.

(As a side note, I think we should start preparing semver releases using
the prepare-release-from-ci script, too, and get rid of
prepare-release-from-npm. I think that was a neat idea originally but
because we already run `npm pack` before storing the artifacts in CI,
there's really not much additional safety; the only safeguard it adds is
the requirement that a "next" release must have already been published.)

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351891433
Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 352064455
Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

[{"sha":"0f1b6628fc4c8045ceed129ba4786f8e6e4d9371","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Refactor for case BuiltinOperator_GATHER in flatbuffer_conversions","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/0f1b6628fc4c8045ceed129ba4786f8e6e4d9371"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

[{"sha":"0f1b6628fc4c8045ceed129ba4786f8e6e4d9371","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Refactor for case BuiltinOperator_GATHER in flatbuffer_conversions","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/0f1b6628fc4c8045ceed129ba4786f8e6e4d9371"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 352064455
Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351891433
Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

[{"sha":"96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"CI: Add broken link checking job for website content

This adds a CI job for running the new PR link checker for documentation.

[terraform-website PR 1574](https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform-website/pull/1574)
added a new link checking CI job specifically for warning about broken links in
pull requests. This link checker is optimized for:

- Running (relatively) quickly.
- Only reporting on files that were changed in the current PR, to avoid spamming
  you with problems you had nothing to do with.
- Being transparent and simple to maintain. (Note that this is in conflict with
  minimizing false positives/negatives! We try to give very few of both, but
  completely eliminating them would result in an unaffordable maintenance
  burden. We expect that some PRs will be merged with this job red.)

The tool is somewhat specific to our Middleman site builder, and we expect it
will be replaced or obviated in the transition to the Next.js platform... but in
the meantime, it should help make documentation slightly easier to maintain.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MartiUK/terraform/commits/96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6"},{"sha":"bf5522aaec0b90de0264f2081fa1814332707d5e","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove website-test task from Makefile

useful way of checking for broken links on a non-production instance of
terraform.io. Also, it didn't include a step for pausing until the server came

Change-Id: I6ea89b0879013b72ad00e1d607223059a482a630","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/dabf3d8057094da094b59cfe445d1c72c0a25317"},{"sha":"706350f02372cbed8ee9dae04aabbc4a5da84760","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Implement round-robin reads.

This enables a new mode of reading from the tf.data service, where consumers read from tasks in a coordinated fashion, instead of the normal first-come first-served.

The main use case for this is coordinated bucketization for synchronous training, where we want to ensure that at each step consumers get batches with elements of similar sizes. This mitigates the inefficiency of some consumers slowly training on large examples while others quickly train on small examples, then block waiting for the slower examples to be processed.

When `consumer_index` and `num_consumers` are specified to `distribute`, each task will enforce a strict round-robin order, where its first element goes to consumer 0, second element to consumer 1, and so on. This requires that all consumers consume the same number of elements.

[{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

* Move traversal logic to ReactFiberCommitWork

The current traversal logic is spread between ReactFiberWorkLoop and
ReactFiberCommitWork, and it's a bit awkward, especially when
refactoring. Idk the ideal module structure, so for now I'd rather keep
it all in one file.

* Traverse commit phase effects iteratively

We suspect that using the JS stack to traverse through the tree in the
commit phase is slower than traversing iteratively.

I've kept the recursive implementation behind a flag, both so we have
the option to run an experiment comparing the two, and so we can revert
it easily later if needed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryota-murakami/react/commits/25b18d31c8b7ffd256416672dc21c50dd22ac3dc"},{"sha":"779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Prevent inlining into recursive commit functions (#20105)

Adds a bunch of no-inline directives to commit phase functions to
prevent them from being inlined into one of our recursive algorithms.

The motivation is to minimize the number of variables in the recursive
functions, since each one contributes to the size of the stack frame.

Theoretically, this could help the performance of both the recursive
and non-recursive (iterative) implementations of the commit phase,
since even the iterative implementation sometimes uses the JS stack.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryota-murakami/react/commits/779a472b0901b2d28e382f3850b2ad09a555b014"},{"sha":"b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Make DevTools Websocket retry delay configurable (#20107)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryota-murakami/react/commits/b6a750be3ca0fc4126ef018e205c951b890c1881"},{"sha":"343d7a4a7eb621a31ba946309b557e0988be3a63","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Fast Refresh: Don't block DevTools commit hook (#20129)

This exposes a host environment (bundler) specific hook to check if an

directly into Flight without needing additional wrapper objects.

* Emit module references as a special type of value

We already have JSON and errors as special types of "rows". This encodes
module references as a special type of row value. This was always the
intention because it allows those values to be emitted first in the stream
so that as a large models stream down, we can start preloading as early
as possible.

We preload the module when they resolve but we lazily require them as they
are referenced.

* Emit module references where ever they occur

This emits module references where ever they occur. In blocks or even
directly in elements.

* Don't special case the root row

I originally did this so that a simple stream is also just plain JSON.

However, since we might want to emit things like modules before the root
module in the stream, this gets unnecessarily complicated. We could add
this back as a special case if it's the first byte written but meh.

* Relax element type check

Since Flight now accepts a module reference as returned by any bundler
system, depending on the renderer running. We need to drastically relax

* Move flow annotation

[{"sha":"0f1b6628fc4c8045ceed129ba4786f8e6e4d9371","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Refactor for case BuiltinOperator_GATHER in flatbuffer_conversions","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/0f1b6628fc4c8045ceed129ba4786f8e6e4d9371"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

[{"sha":"96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"CI: Add broken link checking job for website content

This adds a CI job for running the new PR link checker for documentation.

[terraform-website PR 1574](https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform-website/pull/1574)
added a new link checking CI job specifically for warning about broken links in
pull requests. This link checker is optimized for:

- Running (relatively) quickly.
- Only reporting on files that were changed in the current PR, to avoid spamming
  you with problems you had nothing to do with.
- Being transparent and simple to maintain. (Note that this is in conflict with
  minimizing false positives/negatives! We try to give very few of both, but
  completely eliminating them would result in an unaffordable maintenance
  burden. We expect that some PRs will be merged with this job red.)

The tool is somewhat specific to our Middleman site builder, and we expect it
will be replaced or obviated in the transition to the Next.js platform... but in
the meantime, it should help make documentation slightly easier to maintain.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/96ec703a8cac64e108a0653cb01da98112b3dec6"},{"sha":"bf5522aaec0b90de0264f2081fa1814332707d5e","author":{"name":"Nick Fagerlund","email":"9956a36b5e6e3cca7ae8066f76f964d5f08c7b1e@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove website-test task from Makefile

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351891433
Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Control dependency flowing between devices should have a higher priority virtual channel than data flows, otherwise there is a risk of control transfer getting stuck behind a large data transfer. Current channel device implementation is simple, it doesn't model such prioritization.

Instead of adding complexity to channel device, tf-sim could let control deps bypass channel device and (magically) flow across devices in zero time. Control deps are small, latency dominated transfers. Channel devices are only good at modeling BW bound transfers, so bypassing channel device for control deps should not be so bad.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351891433
Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

[{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351891433
Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351891433
Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/isanjit3/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: Ib24db15f3d8c66a9bc1060ba951f3f930a346096","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/a70d68b3acb7c248572a9ce2e90a67392e6c689c"},{"sha":"3ca937c9ef47f662bc613b1086476b0b6f2042d8","author":{"name":"Christian Sigg","email":"bf0bb771be8a27677291ada19f594af5450440c6@google.com"},"message":"Add support for copybara inline directives in BUILD and .bzl files.

Open-source BUILD files are mapped to the Google-internal variants and vice-versa using a [copybara](https://github.com/google/copybara) workflow. This change adds a step to this workflow that allows inline directives to (un-)comment code:

```python
cc_binary(
    ...
    srcs = [
        "common_src.cc",
        # copybara:uncomment(<reason here>) "google_only_src.cc",
        "oss_only_src.cc",  # copybara:comment(<reason here>)
    ],
    deps = [
        ":common_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_begin(<reason here>)
        # ":google_only_dep",
        # copybara:uncomment_end_and_comment_begin
        ":oss_only_dep",
        # copybara:comment_end
    ],
)
```

The intended use case is to encode relatively small one-off
differences between internal and OSS BUILD files. Making those differences
explicit and inline will hopefully help contributors to write PRs that don't trip up our internal build, and Googlers to write changes that don't break the OSS build.

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 352064455
Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YINZHI-keji/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

This adds a CI job for running the new PR link checker for documentation.

[terraform-website PR 1574](https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform-website/pull/1574)
added a new link checking CI job specifically for warning about broken links in
pull requests. This link checker is optimized for:

- Running (relatively) quickly.
- Only reporting on files that were changed in the current PR, to avoid spamming

[{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

prepare-release-from-npm. I think that was a neat idea originally but

the requirement that a "next" release must have already been published.)

 * `tensorflow/tools/ci_build/linux/rocm/run_gpu_single.sh` - this mirrors the functionality of upstream CI job - `Linux GPU`  (but for ROCm instead of CUDA)

 * `tensorflow/tools/ci_build/linux/rocm/run_csb_core.sh`

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 352064455
Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

This adds a CI job for running the new PR link checker for documentation.

[terraform-website PR 1574](https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform-website/pull/1574)
added a new link checking CI job specifically for warning about broken links in
pull requests. This link checker is optimized for:

- Running (relatively) quickly.
- Only reporting on files that were changed in the current PR, to avoid spamming
  you with problems you had nothing to do with.
- Being transparent and simple to maintain. (Note that this is in conflict with
  minimizing false positives/negatives! We try to give very few of both, but
  completely eliminating them would result in an unaffordable maintenance
  burden. We expect that some PRs will be merged with this job red.)

[{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351903602
Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 352064455
Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.
